\label{Ex01}
Let \( S \) be a semigroup with the following Cayley table, where the dot represents the zero element of \( S \) in the table.



\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ c | c c c c } 
\textbf{\cc{$S$}} & $\cc{y}$ & $\cc{z}$ & $\cc{u}$ & $\cc{t}$\\ \hline 
$\cc{y}$  & . & . & . & $y$ \\ 
$\cc{z}$  & . & . & $z$  & .\\ 
$\cc{u}$  & $y$  & . & $u$  & .\\ 
$\cc{t}$  & . & $z$  & $z$  & $t$ \\ 
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
We have \( {z}^{+} = t \) and \( {z}^{\ast} = u \), but \( ut = 0 \).
